post_text:
For those that have been able to donate towards the NHS fleece tie blanket project, we sincerely thank you! We are still accepting donations through Monday, October 22, and will be making our blankets before the end of October. We are asking for 2.5 yards of both pattern and solid fleece to make our blankets. Some of the blankets will be going back to our CM community, and the others will be going to the Ronald McDonald House. We are excited to be doing this project and are grateful for your help in making it happen!

Also, the NHS will also be hosting a blood drive on Wednesday, November 7 from noon to 6:00 PM, through LifeServe Blood Center. Walk-ins are certainly welcome, but signing up ahead of time helps us know how many staff to have on hand. If you would like to donate on November 7, please contact dhartgers@collins-maxwell.k12.ia.us with a time you would be available. You will receive an email confirmation back. Thank you!

Spartan State Softball Pep Rally and Send Off:

Our Collins-Maxwell Spartan Softball team got their ticket punched and will be headed to Fort Dodge to play in the State Softball Tournament!

Thank you to all our fans and their support and Spartan Spirit! Please join us for The State Softball Pep Rally/Send Off THIS Sunday, July 15, at 4pm-4:30pm at the softball field in Collins. Bring a chair and your Spartan Spirit!

The Spartan Softball Team plays Newell-Fonda for their first game on Monday, July 16 at 11am.

Today's staff profile: Allie Willman!!
1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I taught special ed my first year at Collins-Maxwell and the last 3 years in 2nd grade.

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I went to Marshalltown High School and Iowa State University for my undergrad. I am currently attending Drake University working towards my masters.

3. What are your hobbies?
I like to travel and go on short weekend road trips, watch Iowa State football and basketball and spend time with my family and friends.

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
Never stop trying. You may not always succeed, but you‚Äôll learn something each time you try.

post_text:
Today's staff profile: Becky Pfeiler!!

1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I teach 4th-5th Grade General Music and 5th-12th Grade Band and am the Assistant Director of the Musical. This is my 3rd year overall at Collins-Maxwell, second year also teaching at the Elementary.

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I grew up in Dyersville, IA and attended Beckman High School, then Wartburg College for my Bachelors Degree in Music Education.

3. What are your hobbies?
I enjoy music (obviously) whether it be listening to it at home, performing, or attending concerts. I also like to cook, try new things and travel. I spent 2 1/2 weeks this summer traveling around Ireland, Scotland and England and had the most amazing time!

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
The best advice I could give to students: Not everything will be easy, but the things in life that are really worth it are never easy.

post_text:
Today's staff profile: Gloria Christie!!

1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I have been a school secretary at Collins-Maxwell for about 35 years. It's been fun watching students grow up and now seeing some of their children come through, as well.

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I grew up in Urbandale and graduated from St. Joseph Academy and the University of Iowa (majored in Elementary Education and Psychology).

3. What are your hobbies?
My grandchildren here and in South Dakota are involved in a variety of activities and I enjoy following them and their teammates. I also enjoy traveling, and plan to do more of it after I retire.

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
My best advice to students is to work hard at everything you do and follow the Golden Rule. Good things will happen!

post_text:
Today's staff profile: Melissa Robinson!!

1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I teach Algebra I, Geometry, Algebra II and Consumer Math. I also am a Middle School Volleyball Coach, Junior Prom Chair and Advisor to the Student Ambassadors.

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I graduated from Dowling Catholic high school and I attended DMACC and graduated from Grand View University with a major in Secondary Education and Mathematics.

3. What are your hobbies?
I enjoy playing adult REC volleyball and slow pitch softball. I like to read, garden, cook, play with my granddaughter and ride jet skis with my sons.

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
Never stop learning. School can teach you many things but the world has knowledge outside of a classroom . Always try to listen more than you speak so you are able to truly hear the world around you.

post_text:
Today's staff profile: Deanna Davis!!

1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I have taught at Collins-Maxwell 25 years. I am currently the 5th grade teacher. Prior to that, I taught K-5 special ed for 20 years, physical science and 9-12 at-risk for 3 years, and a MS special ed associate 1 year. I also coached cheerleading for 15 years.

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I graduated from Collins-Maxwell and Iowa State University

3. What are your hobbies?
I enjoy spending time with my family, reading, and scrapbooking.

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
Stop and think...is what I'm going to say going to make somebody feel good? As my mom always tells me, "You can't give kindness away because it always comes back to you."

I teach 1st grade. This is my 31st year here at C-M.

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I went to New Hampton High school in northeast Iowa and went to college at the University of Northern Iowa (UNI)

3. What are your hobbies?
My hobbies are going to sporting events, gardening, riding my bike, exercising, and going to movies with my family.

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
My advice to students is to work hard, be responsible, and respectful.

post_text:
Today's staff profile: Jill Peters!!

1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I am the PK-12 School Nurse.

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I graduated from Collins-Maxwell High School in 2003. I then went to college at Luther College to their amazing nursing program and had clinicals up at Mayo in Rochester, MN. I furthered my education with an internship at Mayo Clinic in their Pediatric Intensive Care Unit and graduated in 2007.

3. What are your hobbies?
My hobbies are gardening, raising livestock, baking, and spending as much time as I can with my family!

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
Never let anyone tell you that you can't do something. Believe in yourself and achieve those dreams!

Today's staff profile: Hillary Hilbert!!

1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I am teaching 3rd grade at Collins-Maxwell Elementary this school year!

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I grew up on a farm outside of Corwith, Iowa and attended Corwith-Wesley-LuVerne High School, where I graduated in 2011. Upon graduating from high school, I attended the University of Northern Iowa in Cedar Falls where I graduated with a dual major in Elementary and Middle Level Education as well as minors in Literacy and Mathematics Education.

3. What are your hobbies?
I enjoy spending my free time reading a good book, watching reruns of my favorite T.V. shows, and most importantly hanging out with family and friends.

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
My advice for students this school year is a quote I have outside of my classroom door, "When you know better, you do better." ~ Maya Angelou

Collins-Maxwell Middle & High School
October 6, 2017 at 10:21 AM ¬∑

With the impending weather, including thunderstorms, we are having to revise out schedule for tonight, as many other area schools are, to try to get the game in before any lightning. We do realize this may cause some inconveniences, but we wanted to make sure we got all events in and not have to cancel anything. The early release bus times that have been scheduled will still run as scheduled. Thank you all for your flexibility, and GO SPARTANS!!!

Pep Rally - 3pm, Large Gym

Presentation of Homecoming Court & Coronation - 3:30pm, Large Gym

Football game - 5:15pm (National Anthem will be played by the Spartan Band with the colors presented the Maxwell Legion Post 249 and Maxwell Veterans of Foreign Wars Post 8174 will be at 5pm)

**notes: Li'l Spartans Cheer Camp performance and our Dance Team performance will be moved to Senior Night on October 20**

6-12 Special Education Teacher, Head Middle School Football Coach, Head Varsity Girls Basketball Coach, Head Boys and Girls Golf Coach

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I graduated from Pella Community High School in 2010. I then went to William Penn University on a bowling scholarship for 1 year. I transferred to Iowa State University in 2011 and graduated in May of 2015.

Camping, fishing, hunting, golf, bowling, basketball, being involved with our church sports ministry, and spending time with my family.

post_text:
Today's staff profile: Melissa Goering!!

1. What do you do at Collins-Maxwell?
I am the K-12 Teacher Librarian and K-6 computer teacher. I have been at Collins-Maxwell since 1995

2. Where did you go to high school and college?
I graduated from Collins-Maxwell in 1987 and then attended DMACC in Ankeny, Iowa State University, and obtained my MA in Library Science from the University of Northern Iowa

3. What are your hobbies?
My hobbies include reading (of course!) and scrapbooking. I love spending time with my children, Koleton 12 and Kara 11, and my husband Doug. I also enjoy spending time with our 7 grandchildren ages 2 to 18!

4. What's the best piece of advice you can give our students?
My advice to all C-M students is to study hard and try your best always. Also never be afraid or ashamed to ask for help. That's why we are here, to help you!

Teacher Quality Committee Meeting
(Senate File 277 Student Achievement and Teacher Quality Program)

Monday, September 25th
2:30-3:00 pm
C-M MS/HS, Superintendent‚Äôs Office
400 Metcalf, Maxwell IA 50161

Agenda:

1. 17-18 TQ Budget allocations
2. 16-17 TQ carryover allocations
3. Revisit TQ application and make any updates/changes

Notes:

Meeting attendees: Alli Willman, Wes Stover, Jordan Nelson, Chad Grandon, Katie Claeys, Jess Swaab

Start time: 2:37 pm

Minutes:

The TQ Committee decided to allocate the budget equally between the two buildings and the district.

The TQ Committee decided to divide the carryover funds equally between the two buildings and the district.

The team determined the electronic TQ application was successful last year and there is no need for teachers to fill out the reflection form afterwards.

post_text:
Our Athletic Director, Troy Houge, found out yesterday that, due to an error in scheduling and miscommunication between the old and new AD's and FB coaches of the school that we were supposed to host in football next Friday, August 18, they didn't have us on the schedule for next week and, thus, we won't be playing the game.

However, Mr. Houge did reach out to Moravia High School, who had a week 1 opening (August 25), and they will be coming here. So, we lost a game, but we gained one, just a week later, and our schedule is still full.

Also, next Friday night at 6pm, we will be hosting a fall sports kickoff at the football field. The volleyball, cross country, and cheerleading coaches will introduce their teams and say some words, then the football coaches will do the same and conduct an open practice so folks can get a look at what 8 man football will look like.
text:
Our Athletic Director, Troy Houge, found out yesterday that, due to an error in scheduling and miscommunication between the old and new AD's and FB coaches of the school that we were supposed to host in football next Friday, August 18, they didn't have us on the schedule for next week and, thus, we won't be playing the game.

However, Mr. Houge did reach out to Moravia High School, who had a week 1 opening (August 25), and they will be coming here. So, we lost a game, but we gained one, just a week later, and our schedule is still full.

Also, next Friday night at 6pm, we will be hosting a fall sports kickoff at the football field. The volleyball, cross country, and cheerleading coaches will introduce their teams and say some words, then the football coaches will do the same and conduct an open practice so folks can get a look at what 8 man football will look like.
